   {:e #blake3 "065429dea6dda5b5a1ba56767b71c6c64ae997bba7cd058feec955cfc61c42f4" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-33f23d20; Session entity: :recon/trace-34b2153c78f6601e; Session entity: :recon/trace-08c8a9ce0a3d55a3; Session entity: :recon/trace-51a85180b440cfd7; Session entity: :task/t-95e79718; Session entity: :recon/trace-16218288c3e8a3a2; Session entity: :recon/trace-407d393e3b693d52; Session entity: :task/t-86cb4d01; Session entity: :recon/trace-4c1a1b3b467baf32; Session entity: :recon/trace-1c260bbe77e1c525; Session entity: :recon/trace-4f3ffa2f12cd4e43; Session entity: :task/t-e10ea7ca; Session entity: :recon/trace-23b16e94fbfee302; Session entity: :recon/trace-3441e90633912389; Session entity: :recon/trace-41b1cb56a4075b6c; Session entity: :recon/trace-f119907a82fcc31d; Session entity: :recon/trace-8f9bc30cc67877dd; Session entity: :task/t-d7716ea8; Session entity: :recon/trace-1f466dd5b87a4d0f; Session entity: :recon/trace-9ab7791a1f164f32; Session entity: :session/s-1774488629; Session entity: :recon/trace-0e0cb72a79456f62; Session entity: :recon/trace-3bb7b5cc20c3a240; Session entity: :task/t-6f58c3a4; Session entity: :recon/trace-bd466bb102320289; Session entity: :recon/trace-f25de90c49a9587e; Session entity: :recon/trace-13632fa54f061427; Session entity: :task/t-c0dce6d4; Session entity: :recon/trace-00c7fbd6eaa1d404; Session entity: :recon/trace-53ecc4cb1daa24e9; Session entity: :task/t-31ab98ec; Session entity: :recon/trace-d78e8fd80c4d415d; Session entity: :recon/trace-c0b70418bc063a08; Session entity: :recon/trace-78ebc182954f9525\nSession entity: :task/t-b76c998f; EMPIRICAL VALIDATION OF OTSU + SIGMOID: Tested on actual DOGFOOD-2 data (11 primary concept cosines from model2vec on Go CLI). Primary similarities: [0.380, 0.455, 0.507, 0.580, 0.591, 0.610, 0.655, 0.681, 0.685, 0.701, 0.747]. Mean=0.599, stddev=0.113. Otsu optimal threshold: 0.51, intra-class variance 0.0036. Sigmoid temperature (stddev/2): 0.057. Result: 8 STRONG (>0.7 strength), 1 MODERATE (0.49), 2 WEAK (<0.3). Compare: current hard cutoff at 0.20 gives ALL 11 full membership. For secondary concepts (17 cosines from 0.21 to 0.74): sigmoid produces 7 STRONG, 3 MODERATE, 7 WEAK. This is genuine multi-membership — graduated by actual semantic similarity, not binary all-or-nothing. The approach works on real data. Key implementation detail: ConceptAssignment::Joined needs a new 'strength: f32' field. 22 call sites destructure this enum — most use '..' so adding the field is backward compatible. 7 construction sites need updating. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, INV-EMBEDDING-004.; Session entity: :task/t-ff060f5a; Session entity: :task/t-10d8d937; Session entity: :task/t-f3642e8c; DOGFOOD CAL-RETEST RESULT: Score 4.2/10 (up from 3.48). Concept collapse persists — all 5 innate concepts converge to jaccard 0.90-1.00 with identical member sets. The self-calibrating threshold (Otsu) runs at HARVEST time, but concept assignment happens at OBSERVE time. On a fresh store, all 10 observations happen BEFORE the first harvest, so they all use the uncalibrated bootstrap default. The Otsu calibration fires after harvest but there is no second observation cycle to benefit from it. This is a CHICKEN-AND-EGG problem: calibration needs observations to compute optimal threshold, but observations need the calibrated threshold to assign correctly. FIX NEEDED: (1) After braid init, run a BOOTSTRAP CALIBRATION — make 3-5 dummy observations with the innate concept descriptions themselves, harvest, calibrate, then delete the dummy observations. This gives the Otsu algorithm data to work with before real observations start. (2) OR: run incremental calibration after every N observations (not just at harvest). (3) OR: the innate concepts need pre-computed threshold and temperature datoms that are derived from the embedder's known distribution. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, INV-EMBEDDING-004, C9.; NARROW DIAGNOSTIC + STEERING IMPROVEMENT (still needed under ADR-031): Even with self-calibrating threshold, the system should detect and report concept collapse as a pathological state. FrontierKind::Narrow fires when mean jaccard across concept pairs > 0.8, producing 'concepts are converging — try observing a specific file, function, or error message.' Additionally, compute_steering_question (concept.rs:1358) currently produces only 'what connects X to Y?' templates. It should be content-aware: if entity_matches is non-empty, suggest investigating specific matched entities; if surprise > 0.3, suggest what makes this observation different from the concept norm. The fallback to generic templates should be the LAST resort, not the common case. Traces to: INV-GUIDANCE-014, ADR-FOUNDATION-030.; Session entity: :task/t-b7c191a4; Session entity: :task/t-ff108cb0; Session entity: :task/t-ec29636f; ADR-FOUNDATION-031: Self-Calibrating Parameters — parameters are first-class knowledge. PRINCIPLE: In a formal epistemology runtime, every decision boundary (threshold, weight, coefficient) is itself a CLAIM about reality. The concept join_threshold=0.20 claims 'observations with cosine > 0.20 are genuinely related to this concept.' That claim has a truth value and can be wrong. A hardcoded threshold is a claim EXEMPT from the system's own verification mechanism — an axiom in a system whose purpose is to question axioms. This is a self-referential contradiction. From the convergence thesis (ADR-FOUNDATION-014): every piece of information must feed back into the coherence model. A hardcoded constant produces information (which observations match which concepts) but never feeds back to adjust itself. This is an open loop — exactly what NEG-010 prohibits. FORMULATION: Every numerical parameter is a degenerate case of Bayesian inference over the system's own hyperparameters. The bootstrap default is the PRIOR. The calibration function is the POSTERIOR UPDATE. The converged value is the MAP estimate. ADR-FOUNDATION-031: All numerical parameters influencing system behavior must be: (a) stored as datoms (first-class knowledge, not source constants), (b) bootstrapped with an embedder/domain default (the prior), (c) updated by a calibration function after each harvest (the posterior), (d) queryable and inspectable (transparency). Parameters without (c) are acceptable only during bootstrap and must carry UNC-* uncertainty markers. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-014, NEG-010, OBSERVER-4, C9.; THRESHOLD AUTO-CALIBRATION: After each harvest, compute the optimal concept join threshold from the observed cosine distribution. Algorithm: (1) Collect all cosine similarities between observations and their nearest concept (from :exploration/concept Refs + concept embeddings). (2) Compute the bimodal split point — the value that maximizes the gap between 'clearly in' and 'clearly out' observations. This is Otsu's method applied to cosine similarities: find threshold T that minimizes intra-class variance of the two groups (above-T and below-T). (3) Store the computed threshold as :policy/concept-join-threshold datom. (4) Next observation uses this calibrated threshold. Bootstrap: first 5 observations use the embedder default (0.20 for model2vec, 0.65 for hash). After 5+ observations, Otsu takes over. The harvest.rs optimal_threshold function already implements exactly this pattern for crystallization scoring — same math, different input distribution. Convergence property: as the store accumulates observations, the threshold converges to the natural boundary of the embedding space for THIS project's domain. A Go CLI project and a React project will converge to different thresholds because their observation-concept similarity distributions differ. This is C9 compliance: the parameter becomes project-specific without manual tuning. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, C9, OBSERVER-4, INV-EMBEDDING-004.; FIX-INNATE-DESCRIPTIONS: The 5 innate concept descriptions (concept.rs INNATE_CONCEPTS, line 861) are too semantically broad for model2vec. 'Parts of the system and their boundaries — packages, modules, crates, files, services' matches any software observation because model2vec understands the semantics. More discriminative descriptions would help even with a correct threshold. Consider: (1) Shorter, more specific descriptions that emphasize the DISTINGUISHING feature of each concept. (2) Example: 'components' -> 'Discrete parts: individual packages, modules, files, services as isolated units'. (3) Example: 'dependencies' -> 'Relationships between parts: imports, function calls, data flow between modules'. (4) Example: 'invariants' -> 'Rules that must hold: constraints, assertions, contracts, specifications to verify'. This is a content change, not a code change — modify the string literals in INNATE_CONCEPTS. Traces to: INV-EMBEDDING-004, C8.; CRITICAL CORRECTION: The dogfood used model2vec embeddings, NOT hash embeddings. The global model at ~/.braid/models/potion-base-8M/ was discovered by resolve_embedder during both init (innate concept embedding) and observe (observation embedding). The concept embedder-type is :embedder/model2vec for all 5 innate concepts. This means the concept collapse is a model2vec+threshold problem, not a hash embedder problem. Model2vec's join_threshold() returns 0.20 (embedding.rs:227), and model2vec cosine similarity between any Go CLI observation and any innate concept description is 0.34-0.74 — all above 0.20. The innate concept descriptions are too semantically broad ('Parts of the system and their boundaries — packages, modules, crates, files, services' matches literally any software observation with cosine > 0.20). FIX: Raise model2vec join_threshold from 0.20 to 0.40-0.50. The model2vec distribution is dense [0.15-0.40] per the doc comment, but the innate descriptions produce cosines of 0.34-0.74, suggesting the threshold should be closer to the distribution MIDPOINT (0.40), not the low end (0.20). Traces to: INV-EMBEDDING-004, ADR-FOUNDATION-030.; INNATE DESCRIPTION REVISION (still needed under ADR-031): Even with self-calibrating threshold and sigmoid membership, the innate concept descriptions affect the embedding centroid that all observations are compared against. Broad descriptions ('Parts of the system and their boundaries — packages, modules, crates, files, services') produce centroids that are equidistant from most software observations, limiting discrimination even with a perfect threshold. Revised descriptions with distinct lead semantics improve the initial centroid separation, giving the calibration loop a better starting point. This is the PRIOR in Bayesian terms — a better prior converges faster. Descriptions: components -> 'Discrete isolated parts: individual packages, modules, files as bounded units', dependencies -> 'Relationships and connections: imports, function calls, data flow paths between modules', invariants -> 'Rules and constraints: assertions that must hold, contracts to verify, specifications to enforce', patterns -> 'Recurring structures: repeated idioms, architectural conventions, protocol templates', anomalies -> 'Defects and surprises: bugs, violations, inconsistencies, unexpected behaviors, test failures'. Traces to: INV-EMBEDDING-004, C8, ADR-FOUNDATION-031.; SIGMOID SOFT MEMBERSHIP: Replace the hard cutoff (sim >= threshold -> binary in/out) with a sigmoid gradient. A hard cutoff claims infinite confidence in the threshold value. A sigmoid says 'my confidence in the boundary has finite precision, so membership near the boundary is uncertain.' Formulation: membership_strength = sigmoid((sim - threshold) / temperature) where sigmoid(x) = 1/(1+exp(-x)). At temperature -> 0, this recovers the hard cutoff. At temperature=0.05, observations at threshold +/- 0.05 get partial membership (0.27-0.73). The existing update_centroid_weighted already supports weighted membership via the surprise_weight factor — multiply by membership_strength. The temperature parameter is ITSELF a calibratable parameter under ADR-FOUNDATION-031. It encodes how much we trust the threshold — high confidence -> low temperature -> sharp boundary. The initial temperature should be derived from the observed standard deviation of cosine similarities: temperature = stddev(cosines) / 2. This makes the sigmoid width proportional to the actual spread of the data. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, INV-EMBEDDING-004, OBSERVER-6.; Session entity: :task/t-f08cbd87; DEAD CODE FINDING: explore_candidates (concept.rs:575) searches for :pkg/* entities in the store but NO braid command ever creates :pkg/* entities. The Explore frontier candidate type only fires in unit tests where :pkg/* entities are manually constructed. In production, explore_candidates always returns an empty vec. This means the frontier system only has Deepen and Bridge as viable candidate types in real stores. Explore requires a trace/extractor that creates :pkg/* entities from the project's package structure — this would need a 'braid trace --packages' or similar command that scans go.mod / Cargo.toml / package.json and creates :pkg/* ident datoms. Without this, Explore is dead code. NOT blocking for CCE-FIX — Deepen and Bridge are sufficient when concepts are differentiated. But Explore should either be implemented end-to-end (including entity creation) or documented as requiring manual pkg entity creation. Traces to: INV-GUIDANCE-014, C8.; FIX-THRESHOLD: The model2vec join_threshold of 0.20 (embedding.rs:227) was empirically calibrated from potion-base-8M on DOGFOOD-3 observations, but the calibration was against observations, not against innate concept descriptions. Innate concepts have broad, definitional text ('Parts of the system and their boundaries — packages, modules, crates, files, services') which produces higher cosine with any software observation than observations produce with each other. The threshold should be the midpoint of the similarity distribution between observations and CONCEPTS, not between observations and observations. Empirical evidence from the dogfood: concept similarities ranged 0.34-0.74, so the threshold should be ~0.50 to achieve ~50% selectivity (top half matches, bottom half rejected). This is a one-line fix: change line 227 of embedding.rs from 0.20 to 0.50. Also update the doc comment to explain the calibration target. The HashEmbedder's inherited default of 0.65 (from the TextEmbedder trait, line 67) is closer to correct for its sparser distribution. Traces to: INV-EMBEDDING-004.; Session entity: :task/t-2dcd3622; FIX-FRONTIER: The frontier recommendation system (concept.rs compute_steering_question, line 1358) generates only 2-3 templates: 'what connects X to Y?' and 'No connections yet. What else relates to this?'. The frontier_recommendation() function (concept.rs:554) produces structured FrontierRec with kind, target, score, and rationale — but observe.rs (line 813) only falls through to frontier_recommendation when no concepts match. When concepts DO match (which is always at threshold 0.20), the code path hits compute_steering_question instead, which just finds the next OTHER concept and asks 'what connects X to Y?'. The fix: in observe.rs, ALWAYS call frontier_recommendation regardless of concept assignment, and PREFER its output over the generic steering question. The frontier system already has the right architecture (Explore/Deepen/Bridge with E[delta-F(S)] scoring from Session 045) — it's just not being called. Location: observe.rs lines 812-825. Traces to: INV-GUIDANCE-014, ADR-FOUNDATION-030." :op :assert}
